description: Set of sound classes referring to sounds that are immediately understood by listeners as arising from specific objects (rather than being heard more literally as "sounds").

The sound of a simple instrument usually consisting of metal cast in the shape of a hollow cup, whose sides form a resonator which vibrates in a single tone upon being struck by a "clapper" suspended within, or by a separate mallet or hammer.

also: "Animal/Livestock, farm animals, working animals/Cattle, bovinae/Cowbell" and "Music/Musical instrument/Percussion/Cowbell" and "Music/Musical instrument/Bell/Cowbell"
description: A simple metal bell historically tied around the necks of cattle to keep track of their whereabouts.
The sound of a large bell usually encountered in churches where it used either to signify the hour or the time for worshippers to go to church.

The sound of a type of bell which produces a distinctive 'jingle' sound, especially in large numbers. They are commonly produced from a single piece of sheet metal bent into a roughly spherical shape containing a small ball bearing.

also: "Sounds of things/Alarm/Bicycle bell" and "Music/Musical instrument/Bell/Bicycle bell" and "Sounds of things/Vehicle/Non-motorized land vehicle/Bicycle/Bicycle bell"
description: The sound of a percussive signaling instrument mounted on a bicycle for warning pedestrians and other cyclists.

The sound of an acoustic resonator in the form of a two-pronged fork with the prongs formed from a U-shaped bar of elastic metal. It emits a pure musical tone and is frequently used as a standard of pitch to tune musical instruments.
The sound of a musical instrument consisting of multiple tuned bells, usually rung by an automated mechanism to produce a short, characteristic tone or melody.

The sound of an instrument constructed from suspended tubes, rods, bells, or other objects that are often made of metal or wood along with some type of weight the tubes or rods can strike when they or another wind-catching surface are blown by the natural movement of air outside.
Sounds of the art of ringing a set of (typically large) tuned bells in a controlled manner to produce variations in their sounding order.

description: A blast of a horn.
The loud sound of an electronic device installed in a vehicle in an attempt to discourage theft of the vehicle or its contents.
The sound of automobile windows being raised and lowered by a built-in electric motor, controlled by a button or switch.

description: The sound of a vehicle sliding on a road surface as a consequence of its wheels losing sufficient frictional contact.

description: The sound of a motorized vehicle as it passes by a listener close to the vehicle's path. The sound may include engine and tire noise and will typically involve a clear build-up and/or decay of intensity as the vehicle approaches and retreats, as well as possible Doppler shift.

The sound of one or more motor vehicles engaged in a competition to complete a course as quickly as possible. Specialized race cars include many modifications, often making them much louder than common street vehicles.

correlated: {"Heavy engine (low frequency)": "0.65", "Bus": "0.58", "Idling": "0.49", "Medium engine (mid frequency)": "0.48", "Engine": "0.47", "Car": "0.45", "Vibration": "0.40", "Outside, urban or manmade": "0.36", "Traffic noise, roadway noise": "0.34", "Car passing by": "0.32", "Accelerating, revving, vroom": "0.31"}
description: Sounds of large motor vehicles designed to transport cargo on roads.

Sounds of a vehicle braking system in which compressed air is used to transmit force to the brake pads on the wheels. The pneumatic system makes an abrupt hissing sound when the pressure is released by venting the air.
The sound of a pneumatic device mounted on large vehicles designed to create an extremely loud noise for signalling purposes.
The sound of an electronic warning device fitted to many commercial vehicles to alert pedestrians when the reverse gear is engaged, signaling that the vehicle is likely to move backwards.

level5: Ice cream truck, ice cream van
ru: Грузовик с мороженым, фургон с мороженым
description: Sounds of a commercial vehicle that serves as a mobile retail outlet for ice cream, usually during the summer. Ice cream vans often play a repeating nursery-rhyme-style melody from speakers mounted on the vehicle's exterior to attract customers.

correlated: {"Traffic noise, roadway noise": "0.67", "Truck": "0.58", "Car": "0.57", "Car passing by": "0.52", "Air brake": "0.51", "Outside, urban or manmade": "0.48", "Heavy engine (low frequency)": "0.47", "Field recording": "0.42", "Ship": "0.33", "Engine": "0.30"}
description: Interior and exterior sounds of a road vehicle designed to carry many passengers.

The sound of any vehicle that is designated and authorized to respond to an emergency. Since emergency vehicles often need to travel at high speeds, they are frequently fitted with audible sirens to warn other motorists to give way.
The sound of a siren fitted to a ground vehicle used by police when responding to incidents.
The sound of a siren fitted to a vehicle used to transport sick or injured people to a hospital or other medical facility.
The sound of a siren fitted to a vehicle used to transport firefighters and their equipment to an emergency situation.
Sounds of a small motor vehicle, usually with only two wheels. Motorcycles typically lack an external shell and seat riders astride the engine.

correlated: {"Bus": "0.67", "Car passing by": "0.53", "Outside, urban or manmade": "0.52", "Car": "0.49", "Field recording": "0.40", "Truck": "0.34", "Toot": "0.31"}
description: The combined sounds of many motor vehicles traveling on roads.
Sounds associated with wheeled vehicles running on rails (tracks).

correlated: {"Railroad car, train wagon": "0.99", "Clickety-clack": "0.91", "Subway, metro, underground": "0.81", "Train wheels squealing": "0.76"}
description: The sound of one or more coupled vehicles running on a rail track to transport cargo or passengers, propelled by a separate locomotive or individual motors in each railroad car.
The sound of an audible signaling device on a steam locomotive used to warn that the train is approaching, and to communicate with rail workers.
The sound of an air horn which serves as an audible warning device on diesel and electric locomotives.

correlated: {"Train": "0.99", "Clickety-clack": "0.94", "Train wheels squealing": "0.78", "Subway, metro, underground": "0.78", "Train horn": "0.49", "Train whistle": "0.31"}
description: The sound of a vehicle used for carrying cargo or passengers on a rail transport system.
The high-pitched tones caused by steel train wheels rubbing against rails, for instance when traversing a tight bend or when braking.
Sounds of high-capacity electric railways that serve as public transport, generally in urban areas.
Sound of vehicles that fly by gaining support from the air.
The sound of the part of an aircraft that generates mechanical power. Aircraft engines are almost always lightweight piston engines, gas turbines, or, in small multicopter UAVs, electric motors.
The sound of an internal combustion airbreathing engine that generates thrust by discharging a fast-moving jet of gas. Jet aircraft use such engines for long-distance travel.
The sound of an aircraft propulsion system that converts rotary motion from an engine via a rotating set of blades into forward thrust through the air.
Sounds of a type of rotorcraft in which lift and thrust are supplied by rotors. This allows the helicopter to take off and land vertically, to hover, and to fly forward, backward, and laterally.

correlated: {"Aircraft engine": "0.75", "Propeller, airscrew": "0.58", "Field recording": "0.50", "Jet engine": "0.47", "Car": "0.32", "Outside, urban or manmade": "0.30"}
description: Sounds of an aircraft capable of flight using wings that generate lift caused by the vehicle's forward airspeed and the shape of the wings.
Sounds of human-powered vehicles used on roads or elsewhere on land.

correlated: {"Outside, urban or manmade": "0.41", "Flap": "0.40", "Gurgling": "0.39", "Outside, rural or natural": "0.37", "Boat, Water vehicle": "0.31", "Fire": "0.31", "Wind": "0.30"}
description: Sounds of a human-powered, pedal-driven vehicle, having two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other.

also: "Sounds of things/Bell/Bicycle bell" and "Sounds of things/Alarm/Bicycle bell" and "Music/Musical instrument/Bell/Bicycle bell"
description: The sound of a percussive signaling instrument mounted on a bicycle for warning pedestrians and other cyclists.

Sounds of a type of sports equipment consisting of a board mounted on two pairs of wheels. A skateboard is typically propelled by pushing with one foot while the other remains on the board, or by simply standing on the deck while on a downward slope and allowing gravity to propel the board and rider.

The sound of a machine designed to produce mechanical energy. Combustion engines burn a fuel to create heat, which then creates a force. Electric motors convert electrical energy into mechanical motion. Other classes of engines include pneumatic motors and clockwork motors.
The sound of an internal combustion airbreathing engine that generates thrust by discharging a fast-moving jet of gas. Jet aircraft use such engines for long-distance travel.
The sound of a small engine such as a toy car, sewing machine, or moped.

also: "Sounds of things/Tools/Power tool/Drill/Dental drill, dentist's drill"
description: The sound of a small, high-speed drill used during dental procedures, usually to remove decay and shape tooth structure prior to the insertion of a filling or crown.
The sound of a machine utilizing one or more revolving blades to cut grass, powered by an electric motor, a small internal combustion engine, or by a human pushing the machine.
The sound of a portable mechanical saw which cuts with a set of teeth attached to a rotating chain. Chainsaws are commonly powered by a small two-stroke internal combustion engine.

description: The sound of a moderately-sized engine such as that which powers a motorcycle, sedan, or small truck.

description: The sound of a large, heavy-duty internal combustion engine, such as that which powers a large truck, locomotive, or ship.  Jet engines, steam engines, rocket engines etc. are excluded.

A metallic "pinging" sound caused by a malfunctioning spark-ignited internal combustion engine. Engine knocking indicates that the combustion of the air/fuel mixture in the cylinder is occurring at the wrong point in the piston's stroke.
The sound of an engine starting from rest, which may involve a specific starter mechanism (as in a standard car).

description: The sound of an engine (typically in an automobile) running without any load and at minimal RPM.

description: The sound made by the engine of a vehicle undergoing acceleration, usually involving an increase in loudness and a rising pitch.
Sounds that suggest they have been recorded in the home.

description: Sounds of a moving structure used to open or close an entrance to an enclosed space such as a building or vehicle.
The sound of a signaling device typically placed near a building's entrance with which a visitor can announce their presence to occupants.
A multi-tone chime made by a doorbell.

correlated: {"Cupboard open or close": "0.40", "Drawer open or close": "0.39", "Inside, large room or hall": "0.36", "Slam": "0.33"}
description: The sound of a type of door which opens horizontally by sliding, usually parallel to a wall.

correlated: {"Thump, thud": "0.49", "Inside, large room or hall": "0.39", "Basketball bounce": "0.37", "Sliding door": "0.33", "Bouncing": "0.30"}
description: The sound of a door or other hinged cover being closed violently.
A sharp noise of a rigid surface being struck, usually without damage and deliberately, most often with the knuckles of the hand.
The sound of a light collision between a rigid object and a rigid surface, for instance to deliberately attract attention.
A short, high-pitched noise without a sharp attack.
The sound of the door to a storage cabinet being opened or closed.
The sound of the opening or closing of a box-shaped container that fits into a piece of furniture in such a way that it can be drawn out horizontally to reach its contents.
The sound of non-destructive collisions between plates, dishes, glassware, cooking vessels, and kitchen and eating utensils.
The sounds of hand implements such as knife, fork, and spoon, that are typically made of steel and are used in preparing, serving, and eating food in the Western world.
The sound of cutting ingredients into pieces with a knife or similar blade tool.
The sound of cooking food in oil or another fat.

Sounds made by a kitchen appliance that heats food by exposing it to microwave radiation, including the noise of the fan, rotation mechanism, and microwave source, as well as the alert sound used to indicate that cooking is complete.

The sound of a kitchen and laboratory appliance used to mix, purée, or emulsify food and other substances, usually by means of metal blades at the base of a container spun rapidly by an electric motor.
The sound of a hand-operated valve controlling the release of water, for instance as fitted to a sink or bath, and the resulting water flow.
Sounds originating from a bowl-shaped plumbing fixture that stores and drains water and that is used for washing hands, dishwashing, and other purposes.
Sounds originating from a large container for holding water in which a person may bathe.
The sound of an electromechanical device designed to blow normal or hot air over damp hair, in order to dry the hair.
The sound of a toilet flushing water along with any waste through a drainpipe.
Sounds of an instrument used to clean the teeth and gums consisting of a head of tightly clustered bristles mounted on a handle.
The sound of a toothbrush that makes rapid, automatic bristle motions driven by an electric motor in order to clean teeth.
The sound of a device that uses an air pump to create a partial vacuum to suck up dust and dirt, usually from floors and other surfaces such as upholstery and draperies.
The sound of a device consisting of two rows of small interlocking teeth for binding the edges of an opening of fabric or other flexible material, like on a garment or a bag.
Sounds made by the mutual collision of small pieces of metal, which are often linked on a ring, used to operate locks.
The sound of a small, flat, round piece of hard material such as metal or plastic colliding with or bouncing on a hard surface.
The sound of hand-operated shearing tools consisting of a pair of metal blades pivoted so that the sharpened edges slide against each other when the handles opposite to the pivot are closed.
The sound of a bladed tool primarily used in the removal of unwanted body hair where the blades are continually moved by an electric motor.
The sound of playing cards being manually rearranged into a random order.
The sound of writing or inputting text by pressing keys on a typewriter, computer keyboard, cell phone, or calculator.
Sounds of a mechanical or electromechanical machine for printing characters by means of keyboard-operated types striking a ribbon to transfer ink or carbon impressions onto paper.
Sounds created by a typewriter-style device which uses an arrangement of buttons or keys controlling switches to enter text or other information into a computer or other electronic device.
The sound of inscribing signs and symbols, most often by using a purpose-made hand-held device, such as a pen or pencil, directly upon paper or similar media.
The sound of an automatic signal warning of danger.

description: The sound of a motor vehicle accessory whose purpose is to provide an audible alert of the vehicle's presence.

description: A blast of a horn.
The loud sound of an electronic device installed in a vehicle in an attempt to discourage theft of the vehicle or its contents.

also: "Sounds of things/Vehicle/Motor vehicle (road)/Truck/Air horn, truck horn"
description: The sound of a pneumatic device mounted on large vehicles designed to create an extremely loud noise for signalling purposes.
The sound of a signaling device typically placed near a building's entrance with which a visitor can announce their presence to occupants.
A multi-tone chime made by a doorbell.

The sound of a telecommunications device that permits two or more users to conduct a conversation when they are too far apart to be heard directly.  This class covers sounds associated with the device itself, not voice that has been carried via the telephone network.
The sound of a physical or synthesized electric bell ringing to signal an incoming telephone call.
The synthesized or pre-recorded sounds made by contemporary electronic telephones to indicate an incoming call or text message.
The sound of a telephony signaling system where short combinations of tones within the frequency range of human speech are used to transmit individual digits.
The sound of a signal that a telephone exchange or other switching equipment sends to a telephone to confirm that it is ready to initiate a connection.

A sound (usually a simple repeating tone) played over a telephone line to indicate that the requested connection could not be completed, for instance because the remote party is already engaged in a different call.
Sounds made by a clock that is designed to make an audible signal at a specific time. The primary use of alarm clocks is to awaken people from their night's sleep.

The sound of a loud noise-making device used to provide warnings to people nearby. A siren typically consists of a single pitch that changes either smoothly or abruptly on timescales around one second.
The sound of a siren fitted to a ground vehicle used by police when responding to incidents.
The sound of a siren fitted to a vehicle used to transport sick or injured people to a hospital or other medical facility.

also: "Sounds of things/Vehicle/Motor vehicle (road)/Emergency vehicle/Fire engine, fire truck (siren)"
description: The sound of a siren fitted to a vehicle used to transport firefighters and their equipment to an emergency situation.
The sound of a siren used to provide emergency population warning of approaching danger such as hurricanes, earthquakes, or military attacks.
Sounds of a mechanical, electromechanical, or piezoelectric signaling device that emits a steady, highly-audible tone with a spectrum extending to high frequencies.
Sounds emitted by a device that senses smoke, typically to warn of a fire.
Sounds of a system designed to warn people when smoke, fire, carbon monoxide or other emergencies are present. Alarms can be either motorized bells or wall-mountable sounders or horns.
A signaling sound used primarily in foggy conditions to warn watercraft of the presence of nearby vessels or other navigational hazards.
The sound of an instrument that produces sound from a stream of forced air.
The sound of a device used to produce sound with the aid of live steam, which acts as a vibrating system.
Sounds that originate from human-created machinery and devices.
The sound of a mechanical device that allows continuous linear or rotary motion in only one direction while preventing motion in the opposite direction.
Sounds made by an instrument designed to keep and indicate time.
A metallic tapping sound.
A steady recurrent ticking sound as made by a clock.
Sounds of rotating machine parts having cut teeth, or cogs, which mesh with other toothed parts to transmit torque.
Sounds of a wheel on an axle or shaft that is designed to support movement and change of direction of a taut cable or belt along its circumference.
Sounds of a machine used to stitch fabric and other materials together with thread.
Sounds of a machine used to create air flow via the motion of a rotating arrangement of vanes or blades.
The sound of a device that removes heat from the air inside a building or vehicle, thus lowering the air temperature.
Sounds of a mechanical or electronic device for registering and calculating transactions, usually attached to a drawer for storing cash.
Sounds of a computer peripheral which makes a persistent human readable representation of graphics or text on paper or similar physical media.
Sounds of mechanical or electronic instruments that employ optics to record or capture images.
Sounds of camera that uses a mirror and prism system to permit the photographer to view through the lens and see exactly what will be captured.
Sounds associated with any physical item that can be used to achieve a goal, especially if the item is not consumed in the process.
Sounds made by a tool or device that delivers a blow to an object. Most hammers are hand tools used to drive nails, fit parts, forge metal, and break apart objects.
The sound of a pneumatic or electro-mechanical tool that combines a hammer directly with a chisel, usually used to break up rock, pavement, and concrete.
Sounds of a tool consisting of a tough blade, wire, or chain with a hard toothed edge, used to cut through material, most often wood.  Includes both manual and motorized saws.
Sounds of a common wood- and metal-working tool used to remove fine amounts of material from a workpiece.

The sounds of a surface being scraped by an abrasive material affixed to sheets of paper or cloth, either to make the surface smoother, remove a layer of material, or sometimes to make the surface rougher.
Sounds of tools that employ a power source other than the manual labor used with hand tools. The most common types of power tools use electric motors.
Sounds of a tool used for making holes in various materials via a rotating drill bit.

also: "Sounds of things/Engine/Light engine (high frequency)/Dental drill, dentist's drill"
description: The sound of a small, high-speed drill used during dental procedures, usually to remove decay and shape tooth structure prior to the insertion of a filling or crown.
The sound of a rapid increase in volume and release of energy in an extreme manner, usually with the generation of high temperatures and the release of gases.
The sound of the discharge of a firearm, or multiple such discharges.
Sounds of a fully automatic mounted or portable firearm, designed to fire bullets in quick succession from an ammunition belt or magazine, typically at a rate of 300 to 1800 rounds per minute.
The sound of the simultaneous and continuous firing of a group of firearms on command.
The sound of large military weapons built to fire munitions far beyond the range and power of infantry's small arms.
The sound of a toy gun that creates a loud sound simulating a gunshot and a puff of smoke when a small percussion cap is exploded.
Sounds of a class of low explosive pyrotechnic devices used for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
The sound of a small explosive device primarily designed to produce a large amount of noise, especially in the form of a loud bang.

correlated: {"Bang": "0.51", "Smash, crash": "0.44", "Eruption": "0.41", "Whoosh, swoosh, swish": "0.40", "Boom": "0.39", "Artillery fire": "0.38", "Whack, thwack": "0.36", "Sound effect": "0.34"}
description: The sound of an enclosure holding gas or liquid coming open suddenly and violently.
The sound of a volcano violently ejecting ash and lava, or a similar event in which large volumes of material are explosively released.
A deep prolonged loud noise.
Sounds associated with the porous and fibrous structural tissue found in the stems and roots of trees, and other woody plants.
The sound of cutting a solid material such as wood into smaller pieces by using an ax or other hacking tool.
The sound of a rigid fibrous material, typically wood, breaking up into splinters or slivers.
Abrupt sounds of individual ruptures in a rigid substance under stress.
Sounds associated with the non-crystalline amorphous solid that is often transparent and has widespread practical, technological, and decorative uses.
A short light metallic sound.
The sound of a brittle rigid substance rapidly breaking into many pieces.
Sounds of a fluid that conforms to the shape of its container but retains a constant volume independent of pressure.
The sound of a liquid colliding with a hard surface.
The sound of small waves of liquid held in a container breaking against the edges.
Sounds made by a liquid-saturated material being squeezed.
The sound of liquid falling in drops.
The sound of liquid being transferred in a steady stream.
The sound of a liquid flowing slowly in an unsteady stream or drops.
The sound of a liquid coming out of a pipe or other opening rapidly and in large volumes.
The sound of a container being filled with liquid.
The sound of a liquid being transferred in a scatter or jet of droplets.
The sound of a liquid being drawn or poured with a pump.
The sound of moving an implement through a fluid substance.
The sound of a liquid that is reaching the temperature at which it transitions to a vapor, resulting in bubbles emerging at the surface.
Portmanteau class for sound categories that clearly suggest specific sources not covered in the other categories.
Sounds associated with underwater sensing via acoustic signals. A classic sonar sound involves reverberant reflections of an emitted tone pip.
Sounds of a shafted projectile that is shot with a bow.

Sounds of a class of stringed instruments consisting of many strings stretched across a thin, flat body, played by strumming or plucking.
Sounds of a small four-stringed guitar-like instument that originated in Hawaii.
Sounds of a musical instrument played using a keyboard, most commonly the piano, organ, and various electronic keyboards, including synthesizers and digital pianos.

Sounds of an electronic keyboard instrument designed to imitate the sound of the pipe organ.
Sounds of an electric organ invented by Laurens Hammond and John M. Hanert in which sliding drawbars create a variety of sounds.

Sounds associated with an electronic musical instrument that generates electric signals converted to sound through amplifiers and loudspeakers or headphones. Synthesizers may imitate instruments such as piano, organ, flute, or vocals; or they may generate novel electronic timbres.

The sound of a small slit drum made from a single piece of wood, making a very short, clean sound.

The sound of an instrument that produces a sound when shaken, usually consisting of a closed rigid shell containing numerous small particles that strike the shell when shaken.

description: A genre and musical form developed by African Americans in the United States around the end of the 19th century from African-American work songs and European-American folk music. The blues form, ubiquitous in jazz and rock and roll, is characterized by the call-and-response pattern, the blues scale and specific chord progressions, of which the twelve-bar blues is the most common. Blues shuffles or walking bass reinforce the trance-like rhythm and form a repetitive groove effect.
Music performed for children, often designed to provide an entertaining means of teaching about cultures, good behavior, facts, and skills.

A genre of music intended to create artistic inspiration, relaxation, and optimism used by listeners for yoga, massage, meditation, and reading as a method of stress management or to create a peaceful atmosphere. Includes both electronic and acoustic forms.
Music performed by one or more singers, with or without instrumental accompaniment, in which singing provides the main focus of the piece.
The rhythmic speaking or singing of words or sounds, often primarily on one or two main pitches called reciting tones.
A melodic sacred utterance believed to have spiritual powers.
A form of vocal percussion primarily involving the art of mimicking drum machines using one's mouth, lips, tongue, and voice.
Group or solo singing without instrumental accompaniment.

Music whose style or form clearly indicates African origin or primarily African influence. Given the vastness of the continent, this covers many distinct musical traditions. Sub-Saharan African music frequently relies on percussion instruments including xylophones, drums, and tone-producing instruments such as the mbira or "thumb piano."
A combination of traditional Nigerian music, Ghanaian music, jazz, highlife, funk, and chanted vocals, fused with percussion and vocal styles, popularised in Africa in the 1970s.
Music that has been written to express either personal or a communal belief regarding Christian life and faith. Its forms vary widely across the world, according to culture and social context.

A genre of Christian music usually featuring dominant vocals with Christian lyrics. Gospel music is rooted in the black oral tradition, in which hymns and sacred songs were repeated in call and response fashion, with hand clapping and foot stomping as rhythmic accompaniment.
Musical styles originating from a large number of Asian countries located in Central, Southern, and East Asia.

A system of music commonly associated with the southern India, whose main emphasis is on vocal music. Although improvisation plays an important role, Carnatic music is mainly sung through compositions.
Hindi film songs featured in Bollywood films. Bollywood songs, along with dance, are a characteristic motif of Hindi cinema which gives it enduring popular appeal, cultural value, and context.

A music genre that originated in Jamaica in the late 1950s, combining elements of Caribbean mento and calypso with American jazz and rhythm and blues. It is characterized by a walking bass line accented with rhythms on the off-beat.
Musical forms that have origins many generations into the past, commonly without formal notation or description, commonly familiar to people in a given culture.

The sound of a single, hard exhalation through the nose.

Inhale audibly through the nose.
